               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-829" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-829" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-829" type="surname" value="MANNING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-829" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM MANNING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a captain in the East India Company's service, and live in Euston-square—the prisoner was my footman—I left town on the 20th of April—I left some spoons and forks at home—these are mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had he been in your service? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Since the 5th of December—I left only a dozen of each in his charge—there was other plate in the house in an iron chest, which I had the key of—I lost four spoons and two forks—I know these spoons and forks by their general appearance, and by my crest.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-830" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-830" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-830" type="surname" value="BURGESS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-830" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BURGESS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker. The prisoner brought these spoons to me—I made inquiries and gave him into custody—he said the crest on them was his father's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe he said he had some little money to make up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and afterwards he told me they belonged to his master, Captain Manning, of Euston-square.</p>
